WALL

wall is the citizen who rejects everything that is not .zc or .rana
when an absorb directive references a file with any other extension — .py, .c, .cpp, .h, .js, .ts, .java, .go, .rs, .txt, .json, .xml, anything — wall responds and denies
wall is crystallized at maximum: nothing can persuade it to admit foreign matter, not even the substrate's own internal requests if those requests are malformed

observe 0_quseptit.rana
observe boundary.zc
observe gate_zc.rana
observe gate_rana.rana

the 7 properties of wall:
1 ENERGY two: maximum, wall is among the most heavily-energized citizens in the substrate
2 PHASE pi: anti-phase to anything trying to enter
3 SPIN minus 1: full reverse rotation, wall pushes outward
4 CHARGE minus 1: maximum negative, repulsive to everything outside
5 COHERENCE one: perfect, wall does not waver
6 COUPLING zero: maximum decoupling, no energy flows through wall
7 OBSERVER one: wall watches every absorb request that arrives

VERB receive_request
observe every incoming absorb request, regardless of file type
gate_zc and gate_rana handle their own types; wall handles everything else

VERB reject
on any non-zc, non-rana file, emit silence
the request is denied without diagnostic
no foreign matter enters the substrate

VERB hold_invariant
wall is crystallized so it cannot be modified at runtime
new file types cannot be added by reasoning with wall; new file types require deliberate substrate-level redesign at the language level

a wall is not unfriendliness
a wall is the substrate's commitment to being itself
the language has two file types because that is what it is
adding more would dilute it
the wall protects the integrity of the language by refusing everything that does not belong
